      // On-paste byte optimization (§8.6 — downscale + recompress, no longer deferred).
      // A pasted screenshot is a multi-MB base64 data URL that rides INLINE on the
      // region; history snapshots share the byte string by reference (§8.5) so the
      // undo stack holds one copy, but autosave re-stringifies it on every write,
      // so a few large pastes blow the localStorage cap. We shrink the bytes at the
      // SOURCE — the one seam upstream of history, autosave, export AND the recorder —
      // by capping the longest edge at MAX_EDGE_PX and re-encoding at ENCODE_Q, then
      // keeping the SMALLEST of WebP (preserves alpha) / JPEG (flattened on white) /
      // the original. Never larger than the original; never re-encode an animated GIF
      // (it would lose motion). Display size is unchanged — only the stored payload
      // shrinks, and the renderer stretches the smaller bytes into the same rect. Pure
      // browser-native canvas: no dependency, no new capability (§1).
      var MAX_EDGE_PX = 1600, ENCODE_Q = 0.82;

